        <div xml:id="KT37-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">tōḻi “kaṭitu varuvar” eṉṟu āṟṟuvittatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">The confidante reassuring [her with the words] “he will come quickly”.</p>
          </div>



        <div xml:id="KT37">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                nacaiperi tuṭaiyar nalkalu nalkuvar</l>
<l>                piṭipaci kaḷaiiya peruṅkai vēḻa</l>
<l>                meṉciṉai yāam piḷakku</l>
<l>                maṉpiṉa tōḻiyavar ceṉṟa vāṟē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
               <l>
                <choice>
                    <seg>He who is full of<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">peritu</term> here is probably to be understood adverbially; cf. KT 213.1.</note> yearning [is] also a granting one.<note place="foot">What is the nuance of the figura etymologica <term xml:lang="ta">nalkal nalkuvar</term>? (This rhetorical figure is explained by Nacc. on Tol. Col. 113 as: x <term xml:lang="ta">cey-tal</term>.) Moreover the connection of the first line to the rest is not clear. If this were an independent sentence, a particle marking would be expected. As this is not the case, I see two possibilities: either an antepositioned apposition to the avar of the last line, or, once again, an unmarked aphoristic prelude. In that case the implication would be that HE, in contradistinction to the careful elephant, obviously does not possess much longing, because he wanders in the desert instead of being with HER. Or perhaps also, as is supposed by the <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷavi</term>, a consolation: because he has longing he will be back again soon.</note></seg>
                    <seg>who possesses much longing and is a granting one.</seg>
                </choice>
               </l>
               <l>
                <choice>
                    <seg>The path he went, friend, is one of lovers<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">aṉpiṉa</term>, n.pl., is either to be connected with the elephant couple (as above), or it could be a real predicate noun: "the ways he has gone [are] full of love" (namely that of the elephants).</note></seg>
                    <seg>One of lovers [is] the path taken by him</seg>
                </choice>
               </l>
               <l rend="indent">where the tender-twigged Yām tree<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">yāam</term> is not given by the TL, but it is traditionally understood as a certain kind of tree and as such rather well attested.</note> is split</l>
               <l rend="indent">by the elephant bull to remove the hunger of [his] female.</l>
                
                </lg>
        </div>
